<br>
I am somewhat puzzled as to other peoples ideas of what should be praised and congratulated.<br>
<br>
I understand from this post, and from reading others in the Soap Box, that many people have had bad personal experiences when encountering a member of one of these guilds.  Now, I can certainly see why someone would like to complain when another person, especially one they have not met before, comes and does something to ruin their day.  <br>
<br>
I would also say, that if someone, especially one not met before, helps you or is friendly, they do deserve to be praised and thanked.  Now, that being said, I would say that the lack of posts praising these guilds could be they are not the type to readily help their fellow player on a daily basis.  Either by choice or simply by chance this could be. Therefore, there would be no one to come and post a &quot;praise&quot; to them.  On the other hand, it could even be that they do in fact help out many people, but the people they help are not in the habit of posting on these boards.  <br>
<br>
If the latter case be true, I would hope they would come forward and state their good experiences when they see someone labeling the kind players as anything but.  Until that happens, bad feelings will hover in the minds of those who feel wronged by the guilds and those who do not know any different about these guilds.  <br>
<br>
Now, with all that said, I will come to my point and opinion.  I see here that the original poster decided to “praise” this guild, which is quite all right.  However, I fail to see what there is to praise about the guilds from his post.  He has listed the guilds doing some feats that may be difficult for others to achieve.  I though, do not see why they deserve praise for this?  (Congratulations perhaps)  As another poster stated earlier, these things they have done are not firsts.  In fact several guilds on several servers have accomplished these feats before.  In my opinion as well, these acts do not require praise.  I will keep my praise for those who would do things for selfless reasons.  “Owning a zone” or killing an all powerful creature on a raid, do not strike me as selfless acts.  <br>
<br>
My praise would go to those individuals who do simple selfless acts.  Assisting a lone fellow on a difficult corpse run, being the protector to all newbies for a day, or summoning lone player’s corpse from the top of a tall tower after his group has deserted him (I have had the pleasure of receiving this act,) as well as any other such actions.  I am sure someone in either or all of these guilds that were mentioned possibly did do some such thing of greatness similar to those I give as example.  And if they have not received praise, I will say thank you and well done to them all now. <br>
<br>
Congratulations to them all for becoming strong enough to take on the Master Challenges of the Everquest realm.  But, I still don’t see anything to praise them about.  Come everyone do let us know how they have made your lives a bit happier.  (in Kudos section if you prefer, instead of here.)<br>
<br>
As for raids, I would say they are 99% motivated by Loot.  Someone wanted something from there, or at least can USE something from there.  The other 1% I would say are raids simply for the sake of exploring a new area they had not been to before.  (going in a large group is the safest way)  Why do wizards go on the raid when there is no loot for them to get you ask?? Well, they go so when they wish to get an item from a certain zone, they will be remembered for helping others get the things they need from this zone.  (or outside planes raids, to get a chance at rolling on a nice item that no one else there needs for trading)<br>
<br>
